{{For|the techniques used by mentalists and illusionists, etc. to elicit personal information | Cold reading}}

[[File:HeathensColdReading.JPG|thumb|A play's inaugural reading held at a [[used bookstore]] in [[Boise, Idaho]]]]

Theatrical '''cold reading''' is reading aloud from a [[Manuscript|script]] or other text with little or no [[rehearsal]],<ref>[http://plays.about.com/od/basics/a/coldread.htm Cold Reading During an Audition - How to Cold Read<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> [[Practice (learning method)|practice]] or study in advance. Sometimes also referred to as '''sight reading,''' it is a technique used by [[actor]]s and other performers in [[theatre]], [[television]], and [[film]] [[Performing arts|performance fields]]. 

Cold readings are common in performance classes, and furthermore are employed frequently in actor [[audition]]s to allow the [[theatrical producer|producer]] or [[playwright]] to get a general idea of the actors' performing capabilities.<ref>[http://www.theactingcorps.com/Site/acting-cold-reading.htm Cold Reading, Acting Techniques - The Acting Corps<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> They are also employed by playwrights who need to hear their play read aloud for the first time by actors, and as such they form an initial integral component of the collaborative creative theatrical process, which may or may not include the eventual production of the play itself. (Public performances of cold readings also serve as entertainment in their own right, particularly in the context of [[community theater]],<ref>[http://showbusinessweekly.com/article-1867-free-readings-at-the-public-theater.html Free Readings at The Public Theater<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111014121605/http://showbusinessweekly.com/article-1867-free-readings-at-the-public-theater.html |date=2011-10-14 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.nj.com/cranford/index.ssf/2013/05/staged_readings_of_short_plays.html Staged readings of short plays at Cranford Community Center, May 18 | NJ.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and less public readings can serve as creative incubators for more established playwright and theatrical talent during the course of play development.<ref>[http://readingeagle.com/article.aspx?id=495909 Way, way off Broadway, stars work without reviews<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>)   Many actors and other performers and [[public speaking|public speakers]] take classes and practice at length to improve the quality of their cold readings.

Cold reading can also be used in conjunction with [[improvisation]]s to gauge a performer's ability to perform new works. A good dramatic cold reader is able to communicate with fluency and clarity and to project speech rhythms and rhymes well. The reader should also be able to bring out the intent, mood and characterization of a piece through appropriate articulation and [[body language]].

